1. Files
This section describes the format and naming convention of PHP files.

File Format
Character encoding MUST be set to UTF-8 without BOM
Sublime.app ‚Üí File ‚Ä∫ Save with Encoding ‚Ä∫ UTF-8
Line endings MUST be set to Unix (LF)
Sublime.app ‚Üí View ‚Ä∫ Line Endings ‚Ä∫ Unix
Filename
Letters MUST be all lowercase
e.g. autoloader.php
Words MUST be separated with a hyphen
e.g. app-config.php
‚ñ≤ Table of Contents

2. Skeleton
This section showcases a barebones PHP file with its minimum requirements.

Line by line breakdown:

Line 1: PHP open tag
Line 2: Blank line
Line 3: Your code
Line 4: Blank line
Line 5: End-of-file comment
Line 6: Blank line
<?php

// your code

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Table of Contents

3. PHP Tags
This section describes the use of PHP tags in PHP and PHP/HTML files.

Open tag MUST be on its own line and MUST be followed by a blank line
i.e. <?php ‚Üµ ‚Üµ ...
Close tag MUST NOT be used in PHP files
i.e. no ?>
Open/close tag MUST be on one line in PHP/HTML files
i.e. <?php ... ?>
Short open tag MUST NOT be used
i.e. <? ‚Üí <?php
Short echo tag SHOULD be used in PHP/HTML files
i.e. <?php echo ‚Üí <?=
‚ñ≤ Table of Contents

1. Open Tag
Open tag MUST be on its own line and MUST be followed by a blank line.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php print_welcome_message();
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because <?php is not on its own line.

<?php
print_welcome_message();
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because <?php is not followed by a blank line.

‚úî Correct
<?php

print_welcome_message();
‚ñ≤ PHP Tags

2. Close Tag
Close tag MUST NOT be used in PHP files.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

print_welcome_message();

?>
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because ?> was used.

‚úî Correct
<?php

print_welcome_message();
‚ñ≤ PHP Tags

3. Open/Close Tag
Open/close tag MUST be on one line in PHP/HTML files.

‚úñ Incorrect
<div>
	<h1><?php
	print_welcome_message();
	?></h1>
</div>
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because <?php and ?> are not on one line.

‚úî Correct
<div>
	<h1><?php print_welcome_message(); ?></h1>
</div>
‚ñ≤ PHP Tags

4. Short Open Tag
Short open tag MUST NOT be used.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?

print_welcome_message();
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because <? was used instead of <?php.

‚úî Correct
<?php

print_welcome_message();
‚ñ≤ PHP Tags

5. Short Echo Tag
Short echo tag SHOULD be used in PHP/HTML files.

~ Acceptable
<div>
	<p><?php echo get_welcome_message(); ?></p>
</div>
‚Ü≥ Acceptable, but <?= should be used over <?php echo when possible.

‚úî Preferred
<div>
	<p><?= get_welcome_message(); ?></p>
</div>
‚ñ≤ PHP Tags

4. End of File
This section describes how every PHP file must end.

End-of-file comment:

MUST be included at the end of a file
i.e. // EOF
MUST be on its own line
i.e. ‚Üµ // EOF
MUST be surrounded by blank lines
i.e. ... ‚Üµ ‚Üµ // EOF ‚Üµ
‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

print_welcome_message();
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because // EOF is missing.

<?php

print_welcome_message(); // EOF
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because // EOF is not on its own line.

<?php

print_welcome_message();
// EOF
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because // EOF is not surrounded by blank lines.

‚úî Correct
<?php

print_welcome_message();

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Table of Contents

5. Namespaces
This section describes how to use one or more namespaces and their naming convention.

Namespace declaration MUST be the first statement and MUST be followed by a blank line
i.e. <?php ‚Üµ ‚Üµ namespace MyCompany; ‚Üµ ‚Üµ ...
Namespace name MUST start with a capital letter and MUST be camelcase
e.g. namespace MyCompany;
Multiple namespaces MUST use the curly brace syntax
i.e. namespace MyCompany { ... }
Magic constant SHOULD be used to reference the namespace name
i.e. __NAMESPACE__
‚ñ≤ Table of Contents

1. Namespace Declaration
Namespace declaration MUST be the first statement and MUST be followed by a blank line.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

print_welcome_message();

namespace MyCompany;

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because namespace MyCompany; is not the first statement.

<?php

namespace MyCompany;
print_welcome_message();

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because namespace MyCompany; is not followed by a blank line.

‚úî Correct
<?php

namespace MyCompany;

print_welcome_message();

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Namespaces

2. Namespace Name
Namespace name MUST start with a capital letter and MUST be camelcase.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

namespace myCompany;

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because myCompany does not start with a capital letter.

<?php

namespace MyCOMPANY;

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because MyCOMPANY is not written in camelcase.

‚úî Correct
<?php

namespace MyCompany;

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Namespaces

3. Multiple Namespaces
Multiple namespaces MUST use the curly brace syntax.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

namespace MyCompany\View;

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because there are two namespaces and the curly brace syntax was not used.

‚úî Correct
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model {
	// model body
}

namespace MyCompany\View {
	// view body
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Namespaces

4. Magic Constant
Magic constant SHOULD be used to reference the namespace name.

~ Acceptable
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model {
	// model body
}

namespace MyCompany\View {
	$welcome_message = MyCompany\View\get_welcome_message();
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Acceptable, but using __NAMESPACE__ instead of MyCompany\View is preferred.

‚úî Preferred
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model {
	// ModuleOne body
}

namespace MyCompany\View {
	$welcome_message = __NAMESPACE__ . '\\' . get_welcome_message();
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Namespaces

6. Comments
This section describes how comments should be formatted and used.

Single-line comments MUST use two forward slashes
e.g. // My comment
Multi-line comments MUST use the block format
i.e. /** ‚Üµ * My comment ‚Üµ */
Header comments SHOULD use the block format
i.e. /** ‚Üµ * Name of code section ‚Üµ */
Divider comments SHOULD use the block format with asterisks in between
i.e. /** 75 asterisks */
Comments MUST be on their own line
i.e. ‚Üµ // My comment
Blocks of code SHOULD be explained or summarized
e.g. // Compare user accounts from export against expired accounts in system
Ambiguous numbers MUST be clarified
e.g. // 1,000 processable records per hour API limit
External variables MUST be clarified
e.g. // Database object included in file.php
‚ñ≤ Table of Contents

1. Single-line Comments
Single-line comments MUST use two forward slashes.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

/* This is a comment */

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because it uses /* and */ for a single-line comment.

‚úî Correct
<?php

// This is a comment

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Comments

2. Multi-line Comments
Multi-line comments MUST use the block format.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

// This is a
// multi-line
// comment

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because it uses // for a multi-line comment.

‚úî Correct
<?php

/**
 * This is a
 * multi-line
 * comment
 */

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Comments

3. Header Comments
Header comments SHOULD use the block format.

<?php

/**
 * Global application settings
 */

define('SETTING_ONE', '');
define('SETTING_TWO', '');
define('SETTING_THREE', '');

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Comments

4. Divider Comments
Divider comments SHOULD use the block format with 75 asterisks in between.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

/**#######################################################################*/

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because it uses # instead of *.

<?php

/*************/

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because it uses 10 instead of 75 *.

‚úî Correct
<?php

/**
 * Beginning + Middle + End
 * 3 spaces + 75 spaces + 2 spaces = 80 character line limit
 */

/******************************************************************************/

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Comments

5. Comments
Comment MUST be on their own line.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

print_welcome_message(); // Prints welcome message

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because // Prints welcome message is not on its own line.

‚úî Correct
<?php

// Prints welcome message
print_welcome_message();

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Comments

6. Blocks of Code
Blocks of code SHOULD be explained or summarized.

~ Acceptable
<?php

foreach ($users as $user) {
	if ($expr1) {
		// ...
	} else {
		// ...
	}
	if ($expr2) {
		// ...
	} elseif ($expr3) {
		// ...
	} else {
		// ...
	}
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Acceptable, but block of code should be explained or summarized.

‚úî Preferred
<?php

/**
 * Get active website bloggers with profile photo for author page.
 * If no photo exists on website, check intranet.
 * If neither location has photo, send user email to upload one.
 */
foreach ($users as $user) {
	if ($expr1) {
		// ...
	} else {
		// ...
	}
	if ($expr2) {
		// ...
	} elseif ($expr3) {
		// ...
	} else {
		// ...
	}
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Comments

7. Ambiguous Numbers
Ambiguous numbers MUST be clarified.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

while ($expr && $x < 1000) {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because 1000 is not clarified.

‚úî Correct
<?php

// Script times out after 1,000 records
while ($expr && $x < 1000) {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Comments

8. External Variables
External variables MUST be clarified.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

include_once 'some-file.php';

// ...

foreach($users as $user) {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because source of $users is not clear.

‚úî Correct
<?php

include_once 'some-file.php';

// ...

// $users from some-file.php
foreach($users as $user) {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Comments

7. Includes
This section describes the format for including and requiring files.

Include/require once SHOULD be used
i.e. include ‚Üí include_once, require ‚Üí require_once
Parenthesis MUST NOT be used
e.g. include_once('file.php'); ‚Üí include_once 'file.php';
Purpose of include MUST be documented with a comment
e.g. // Provides WordPress environment ‚Üµ require_once 'wp-load.php';
‚ñ≤ Table of Contents

1. Include/Require Once
Include/require once SHOULD be used.

~ Acceptable
<?php

include 'some-file.php';
require 'some-other-file.php';

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Acceptable, but _once should be appended to include and require if possible.

‚úî Preferred
<?php

include_once 'some-file.php';
require_once 'some-other-file.php';

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Includes

2. Parenthesis
Parenthesis MUST NOT be used.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

include_once('some-file.php');
require_once('some-other-file.php');

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because include_once and require_once are used with parenthesis.

‚úî Correct
<?php

include_once 'some-file.php';
require_once 'some-other-file.php';

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Includes

3. Purpose of Include
Purpose of include MUST be documented with a comment.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

require_once 'some-file.php';

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because there is no comment as to what some-file.php does or provides.

‚úî Correct
<?php

// Provides XYZ framework
require_once 'some-file.php';

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Includes

8. Formatting
This section outline various, general formatting rules related to whitespace and text.

Line length MUST NOT exceed 80 characters, unless it is text
i.e. |---- 80+ chars ----| ‚Üí refactor expression and/or break list values
Line indentation MUST be accomplished using tabs
i.e. function func() { ‚Üµ ‚á• ... ‚Üµ }
Blank lines SHOULD be added between logical blocks of code
i.e. ... ‚Üµ ‚Üµ ...
Text alignment MUST be accomplished using spaces
i.e. $var ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ = ...;
Trailing whitespace MUST NOT be present after statements or serial comma break or on blank lines
i.e. no ... ¬∑ ¬∑ ‚Üµ ¬∑ ‚Üµ ...
Keywords MUST be all lowercase
e.g. false, true, null, etc.
Variables MUST be all lowercase and words MUST be separated by an underscore
e.g. $welcome_message
Global variables MUST be declared one variable per line and MUST be indented after the first
e.g. global $var1, ‚Üµ ‚á• $var2;
Constants MUST be all uppercase and words MUST be separated by an underscore
e.g. WELCOME_MESSAGE
Statements MUST be placed on their own line and MUST end with a semicolon
e.g. welcome_message();
Operators MUST be surrounded by a space
e.g. $total = 15 + 7;, $var .= '';
Unary operators MUST be attached to their variable or integer
e.g. $index++, --$index
Concatenation period MUST be surrounded by a space
e.g. echo 'Read:' . $welcome_message;
Single quotes MUST be used
e.g. echo 'Hello, World!';
Double quotes SHOULD NOT be used
e.g. echo "Read: $welcome_message"; ‚Üí echo 'Read: ' . $welcome_message;
‚ñ≤ Table of Contents

1. Line Length
Line length MUST NOT exceed 80 characters, unless it is text.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

if(in_array('Slumdog Millionaire', $movies) && in_array('Silver Linings Playbook', $movies) && in_array('The Lives of Others', $movies) && in_array('The Shawshank Redemption', $movies)) {
	// if body
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because expression exceeds 80 characters and should be refactored.

<?php

$my_movies = array('Slumdog Millionaire', 'Silver Linings Playbook', 'The Lives of Others', 'The Shawshank Redemption');

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because arguments exceed 80 characters and should be placed on their own line.

~ Acceptable
<?php

$text = 'Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Donec posuere rutrum tincidunt. Duis lacinia laoreet diam, nec consectetur magna facilisis eget. Quisque elit mauris, auctor quis vulputate id, sagittis nec tortor. Praesent fringilla lorem eu massa convallis ultricies. Maecenas lacinia porta purus, sollicitudin condimentum felis mollis a. Proin sed augue purus. Quisque scelerisque eros vitae egestas porta. Suspendisse vitae purus justo. Pellentesque justo nunc, luctus quis magna sit amet, venenatis rutrum ante. Nam eget nisi ultricies, sodales lectus vel, luctus dui. Cras pellentesque augue vitae nulla laoreet convallis. Mauris ut turpis mollis, elementum arcu eu, semper risus. Mauris vel urna ut felis blandit dictum. Aliquam sit amet tincidunt arcu. Nunc et elit quam. Aliquam hendrerit magna ut lacus semper consequat blandit eu ipsum.';

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Acceptable because line length was exceeded due to text, not code.

‚úî Correct
<?php

$my_movies = array(
	'Slumdog Millionaire',
	'Silver Linings Playbook',
	'The Lives of Others',
	'The Shawshank Redemption'
);

$has_all_movies = true;

foreach($my_movies as $my_movie) {
	if(!in_array($my_movie, $movies)) {
		$has_all_movies = false;
	}
}

if($has_all_movies) {
	// if body
}

$some_long_variable = get_something_else(
	'from_some_other_function',
	'another_long_argument'
);

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

2. Line Indentation
Line indentation MUST be accomplished using tabs.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

function print_welcome_message() {
    echo WELCOME_MESSAGE;
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because spaces are used to indent echo WELCOME_MESSAGE; instead of a tab.

‚úî Correct
<?php

function print_welcome_message() {
	echo WELCOME_MESSAGE;
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

3. Blank Lines
Blank lines SHOULD be added between logical blocks of code.

~ Acceptable
<?php

$my_movies = array(
	'Slumdog Millionaire',
	'Silver Linings Playbook',
	'The Lives of Others',
	'The Shawshank Redemption'
);
$has_all_movies = true;
foreach($my_movies as $my_movie) {
	if(!in_array($my_movie, $movies)) {
		$has_all_movies = false;
	}
}
if($has_all_movies) {
	// if body
}

// EOF
‚Ü≥ Acceptable, but can make scanning code more difficult.

‚úî Preferred
<?php

$my_movies = array(
	'Slumdog Millionaire',
	'Silver Linings Playbook',
	'The Lives of Others',
	'The Shawshank Redemption'
);

$has_all_movies = true;

foreach($my_movies as $my_movie) {
	if(!in_array($my_movie, $movies)) {
		$has_all_movies = false;
	}
}

if($has_all_movies) {
	// if body
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

4. Text Alignment
Text alignment MUST be accomplished using spaces.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

$movie_quotes = array(
	'slumdog_millionaire'		=> 'When somebody asks me a question, I tell them the answer.',
	'silver_linings_playbook'	=> 'I opened up to you, and you judged me.',
	'the_lives_of_others'		=> 'To think that people like you ruled a country.',
	'the_shawshank_redemption'	=> 'Get busy living, or get busy dying.'
);

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because tabs are used instead of spaces to vertically align =>.

<?php

$movie_quotes = array(
    'slumdog_millionaire'       => 'When somebody asks me a question, I tell them the answer.',
    'silver_linings_playbook'   => 'I opened up to you, and you judged me.',
    'the_lives_of_others'       => 'To think that people like you ruled a country.',
    'the_shawshank_redemption'  => 'Get busy living, or get busy dying.'
);

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because spaces are used instead of tabs to indent array keys.

‚úî Correct
<?php

$movie_quotes = array(
	'slumdog_millionaire'       => 'When somebody asks me a question, I tell them the answer.',
	'silver_linings_playbook'   => 'I opened up to you, and you judged me.',
	'the_lives_of_others'       => 'To think that people like you ruled a country.',
	'the_shawshank_redemption'  => 'Get busy living, or get busy dying.'
);

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

5. Trailing Whitespace
Trailing whitespace MUST NOT be present after statements or serial comma break or on blank lines.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

$quotes_exist = false;  

print_welcome_message();

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because there are two spaces after $quotes_exist = false;.

<?php

$my_movies = array(
	'Slumdog Millionaire', 
	'Silver Linings Playbook', 
	'The Lives of Others', 
	'The Shawshank Redemption'
);

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because there is a space after ,.

<?php

$quotes_exist = false;
  
print_welcome_message();

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because there are two spaces on the blank line below $quotes_exist = false;.

‚úî Correct
<?php

$quotes_exist = false;

print_welcome_message();

// EOF
 
<?php

$my_movies = array(
	'Slumdog Millionaire',
	'Silver Linings Playbook',
	'The Lives of Others',
	'The Shawshank Redemption'
);

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

6. Keywords
Keywords MUST be all lowercase.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

$is_true = FALSE;
$is_false = TRUE:
$movie_quote = NULL;

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because FALSE, TRUE and NULL are not all lowercase.

‚úî Correct
<?php

$is_true = false;
$is_false = true:
$movie_quote = null;

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

7. Variables
Variables MUST be all lowercase and words MUST be separated by an underscore.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

$welcome_Message = '';
$Welcome_Message = '';
$WELCOME_MESSAGE = '';

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because $welcome_Message, $Welcome_Message and $WELCOME_MESSAGE are not all lowercase.

<?php

$welcomemessage = '';

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because welcome and message are not separated with an underscore.

‚úî Correct
<?php

$welcome_message = '';

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

8. Global Variables
Global variables MUST be declared one variable per line and MUST be indented after the first.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

global $app_config, $cache, $db_connection;

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because $app_config, $cache and $db_connection are together on one line.

<?php

global $app_config,
$cache,
$db_connection;

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because $db_connection and $cache are not indentend once.

‚úî Correct
<?php

global $app_config,
	$cache,
	$db_connection;

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

9. Constants
Constants MUST be all uppercase and words MUST be separated by an underscore.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

define('welcome_Message', '');
define('Welcome_Message', '');
define('welcome_message', '');

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because welcome_Message, Welcome_Message and welcome_message are not all uppercase.

<?php

define('WELCOMEMESSAGE', '');

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because WELCOME and MESSAGE are not separated with an underscore.

‚úî Correct
<?php

define('WELCOME_MESSAGE', '');

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

10. Statements
Statements MUST be placed on their own line and MUST end with a semicolon.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

$quotes_exist = false; print_welcome_message();

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because $quotes_exist = false; and print_welcome_message(); are on one line.

<div>
	<h1><?= print_welcome_message() ?></h1>
</div>
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because print_welcome_message() is missing a semicolon.

‚úî Correct
<?php

$quotes_exist = false;
print_welcome_message();

// EOF
 
<div>
	<h1><?= print_welcome_message() ?></h1>
</div>
‚ñ≤ Formatting

11. Operators
Operators MUST be surrounded a space.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

$total=3+14;
$string='Hello, World! ';
$string.='Today is a good day!';

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because there is no space surrounding the =, + or .= sign.

‚úî Correct
<?php

$total = 3 + 14;
$string = 'Hello, World! ';
$string .= 'Today is a good day!';

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

12. Unary Operators
Unary operators MUST be attached to their variable or integer.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

$index ++;
-- $index;

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because there is a space before ++ and after --.

‚úî Correct
<?php

$index++;
--$index;

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

13. Concatenation Period
Concatenation period MUST be surrounded by a space.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

echo 'Hello, World! Today is '.$date.'!';

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because there is no space surrounding ..

‚úî Correct
<?php

echo 'Hello, World! Today is ' . $date . '!';

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

14. Single Quotes
Single quotes MUST be used.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

echo "Hello, World!";

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because "Hello, World!" is not written with single quotes.

‚úî Correct
<?php

echo 'Hello, World!';

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

15. Double Quotes
Double quotes SHOULD NOT be used.

~ Acceptable
<?php

echo "Hello, World! Today is $date!";

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Acceptable, but burries the $date variable, which is why single quotes are preferred.

<?php

echo "Hello, World! He's watching movies and she's reading books.";

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Acceptable when long pieces of text have apostrophies that would need to be escaped.

‚úî Preferred
<?php

echo 'Hello, World! Today is ' . $date . '!';

echo 'Hello, World! He\'s watching movies and she\'s reading books.';

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Formatting

9. Functions
This section describes the format for function names, calls, arguments and declarations.

Function name MUST be all lowercase and words MUST be separated by an underscore
e.g. function welcome_message() {
Function prefix MUST start with verb
e.g. get_, add_, update_, delete_, convert_, etc.
Function call MUST NOT have a space between function name and open parenthesis
e.g. func();
Function arguments
MUST NOT have a space before the comma
MUST have a space after the comma
MAY use line breaks for long arguments
MUST then place each argument on its own line
MUST then indent each argument once
MUST be ordered from required to optional first
MUST be ordered from high to low importance second
MUST use descriptive defaults
MUST use type hinting
e.g. func($arg1, $arg2 = 'asc', $arg3 = 100);
Function declaration MUST be documented using phpDocumentor tag style and SHOULD include
Short description
Optional long description, if needed
@access: private or protected (assumed public)
@author: Author name
@global: Global variables function uses, if applicable
@param: Parameters with data type, variable name, and description
@return: Return data type, if applicable
Function return
MUST occur as early as possible
MUST be initialized prior at top
MUST be preceded by blank line, except inside control statement
i.e. if (!$expr) { return false; }
‚ñ≤ Table of Contents

1. Function Name
Function name MUST be all lowercase and words MUST be separated by an underscore.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

get_Welcome_Message();
Get_Welcome_Message();
GET_WELCOME_MESSAGE();

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because the function names are not all lowercase.

<?php

getwelcomemessage();

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because get, welcome and message are not separated with an underscore.

‚úî Correct
<?php

get_welcome_message();

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Functions

2. Function Prefix
Function prefix MUST start with verb.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

active_users();
network_location($location1, $location2);
widget_form($id);

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because functions are not prefixed with a verb.

‚úî Correct
<?php

get_active_users();
move_network_location($location1, $location2);
delete_widget_form($id);

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Functions

3. Function Call
Function call MUST NOT have a space between function name and open parenthesis.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

print_welcome_message ();

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because there is a space between get_welcome_message and ().

‚úî Correct
<?php

print_welcome_message();

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Functions

4. Function Arguments
Function arguments:

MUST NOT have a space before the comma
MUST have a space after the comma
MAY use line breaks for long arguments
MUST then place each argument on its own line
MUST then indent each argument once
MUST be ordered from required to optional first
MUST be ordered from high to low importance second
MUST use descriptive defaults
MUST use type hinting
‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

my_function($arg1 , $arg2 , $arg3);

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because there is a space before ,.

<?php

my_function($arg1,$arg2,$arg3);

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because there is no space after ,.

<?php

my_other_function($arg1_with_a_really_long_name,
	$arg2_also_has_a_long_name,
	$arg3
);

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because $arg1_with_a_really_long_name is not on its own line.

<?php

my_other_function(
$arg1_with_a_really_long_name,
$arg2_also_has_a_long_name,
$arg3
);

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because arguments are not indented once.

<?php

function get_objects($type, $order = 'asc', $limit) {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because $type, $order and $limit are not in order of required to optional.

<?php

function get_objects($limit, $order, $type) {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because $limit, $order and $type are not in order of importance.

<?php

function get_objects($type, $order = true, $limit = 100) {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because true is not a descriptive default for $order.

<?php

function add_users_to_office($users, $office) {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because $users and $office are missing their data type.

‚úî Correct
<?php

my_function($arg1, $arg2, $arg3);

my_other_function(
	$arg1_with_a_really_long_name,
	$arg2_also_has_a_long_name,
	$arg3
);

function get_objects($type, $order = 'asc', $limit = 100) {
	// ...
}

function add_users_to_office(array $users, Office $office) {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Functions

5. Function Declaration
Function declaration MUST be documented using phpDocumentor tag style and SHOULD include:

Short description
Optional long description, if needed
@access: private or protected (assumed public)
@author: Author name
@global: Global variables function uses, if applicable
@param: Parameters with data type, variable name, and description
@return: Return data type, if applicable
‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

function my_function($id, $type, $width, $height) {
	// ...
	return $Photo;
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because my_function is not documented.

‚úî Correct
<?php

/**
 * Get photo from blog author
 * 
 * Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Ut id volutpat 
 * orci. Etiam pharetra eget turpis non ultrices. Pellentesque vitae risus 
 * sagittis, vehicula massa eget, tincidunt ligula.
 *
 * @access private
 * @author Firstname Lastname
 * @global object $post
 * @param int $id Author ID
 * @param string $type Type of photo
 * @param int $width Photo width in px
 * @param int $height Photo height in px
 * @return object Photo
 */
function my_function($id, $type, $width, $height) {
	// ...
	return $Photo;
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Functions

6. Function Return
Function return:

MUST occur as early as possible
MUST be initialized prior at top
MUST be preceded by blank line, except inside control statement
‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

function get_object() {
	$var = false;
	if($expr1) {
		// ...
		if($expr2) {
			// ...
		}
	}

	return $var;
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because get_object does not return as early as possible.

<?php

function get_movies() {
	// ...

	return $movies;
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because $movies is not initialized at top.

<?php

function get_movies() {
	$movies = array();
	// ...
	return $movies;
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because return $movies is not preceded by blank line.

‚úî Correct
<?php

function get_object() {
	$var = false;
	if (!$expr1) {
		return $var;
	}
	if (!$expr2) {
		return $var;
	}
	// ...

	return $var;
}

// EOF
 
<?php

function get_movies() {
	$movies = array();
	// ...

	return $movies;
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Functions

10. Control Structures
This section defines the layout and usage of control structures. Note that this section is separated into rules that are applicable to all structures, followed by specific rules for individual structures.

Keyword MUST be followed by a space
e.g. if (, switch (, do {, for (
Opening parenthesis MUST NOT be followed by a space
e.g. ($expr, ($i
Closing parenthesis MUST NOT be preceded by a space
e.g. $expr), $i++), $value)
Opening brace MUST be preceded by a space and MUST be followed by a new line
e.g. $expr) {, $i++) {
Structure body MUST be indented once and MUST be enclosed with curly braces (no shorthand)
e.g. if ($expr) { ‚Üµ ‚á• ... ‚Üµ }
Closing brace MUST start on the next line
i.e. ... ‚Üµ }
Nesting MUST NOT exceed three levels
e.g. no if ($expr1) { if ($expr2) { if ($expr3) { if ($expr4) { ... }}}}
In addition to the rules above, some control structures have additional requirements:

If, Elseif, Else
elseif MUST be used instead of else if
elseif and else MUST be between } and { on one line
Switch, Case
Case statement MUST be indented once
i.e. ‚á• case 1:
Case body MUST be indented twice
i.e. ‚á• ‚á• func();
Break keyword MUST be indented twice
i.e. ‚á• ‚á• break;
Case logic MUST be separated by one blank line
i.e. case 1: ... break; ‚Üµ ‚Üµ case 2: ... break;
While, Do While
For, Foreach
Try, Catch
catch MUST be between } and { on one line
‚ñ≤ Table of Contents

1. If, Elseif, Else
elseif MUST be used instead of else if
elseif and else MUST be between } and { on one line
‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

if ($expr1) {
	// if body
} else if ($expr2) {
	// elseif body
} else {
	// else body
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because else if was used instead of elseif.

<?php

if ($expr1) {
	// if body
}
elseif ($expr2) {
	// elseif body
}
else {
	// else body
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because elseif and else are not between } and { on one line.

<?php

$result1 = if ($expr1) ? true : false;

if($expr2)
	$result2 = true;

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because structure body is not wrapped in curly braces.

‚úî Correct
<?php

if ($expr1) {
	// if body
} elseif ($expr2) {
	// elseif body
} else {
	// else body
}

if ($expr1) {
	$result1 = true;
} else {
	$result1 = false;
}

if ($expr2) {
	$result2 = true;
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Control Structures

2. Switch, Case
Case statement MUST be indented once
Case body MUST be indented twice
Break keyword MUST be indented twice
Case logic MUST be separated by one blank line
‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

switch ($expr) {
case 0:
	echo 'First case, with a break';
	break;

case 1:
	echo 'Second case, which falls through';
	// no break
case 2:
case 3:
case 4:
	echo 'Third case, return instead of break';
	return;

default:
	echo 'Default case';
	break;
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because case 0 thru default are not indented once.

<?php

switch ($expr) {
	case 0:
	echo 'First case, with a break';
	break;

	case 1:
	echo 'Second case, which falls through';
	// no break
	case 2:
	case 3:
	case 4:
	echo 'Third case, return instead of break';
	return;

	default:
	echo 'Default case';
	break;
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because echo, break and return are not indented twice.

<?php

switch ($expr) {
	case 0:
		echo 'First case, with a break';
		break;
	case 1:
		echo 'Second case, which falls through';
		// no break
	case 2:
	case 3:
	case 4:
		echo 'Third case, return instead of break';
		return;
	default:
		echo 'Default case';
		break;
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because case 0, case 1 thru case 4, and default are not separated by one blank line.

‚úî Correct
<?php

switch ($expr) {
	case 0:
		echo 'First case, with a break';
		break;

	case 1:
		echo 'Second case, which falls through';
		// no break
	case 2:
	case 3:
	case 4:
		echo 'Third case, return instead of break';
		return;

	default:
		echo 'Default case';
		break;
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Control Structures

3. While, Do While
‚úî Correct
<?php

while ($expr) {
	// structure body
}

do {
	// structure body;
} while ($expr);

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Control Structures

4. For, Foreach
‚úî Correct
<?php

for ($i = 0; $i < 10; $i++) {
	// for body
}

foreach ($iterable as $key => $value) {
	// foreach body
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Control Structures

5. Try, Catch
‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

try {
	// try body
}
catch (FirstExceptionType $e) {
	// catch body
}
catch (OtherExceptionType $e) {
	// catch body
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because catch is not between } and { on one line.

‚úî Correct
<?php

try {
	// try body
} catch (FirstExceptionType $e) {
	// catch body
} catch (OtherExceptionType $e) {
	// catch body
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Control Structures

11. Classes
This section describes class files, names, definitions, properties, methods and instantiation.

Class file MUST only contain one definition and MUST be prefixed with class-
i.e. class User ‚Üí class-user.php, class Office ‚Üí class-office.php
Class namespace MUST be defined and MUST include vendor name
e.g. namespace MyCompany\Model;, namespace MyCompany\View;, namespace MyCompany\Controller;
Class name MUST start with a capital letter and MUST be camelcase
e.g. MyCompany
Class documentation MUST be present and MUST use phpDocumentor tag style
i.e. @author, @global, @package
Class definition MUST place curly braces on their own line
i.e. class User ‚Üµ { ‚Üµ ... ‚Üµ }
Class properties
MUST follow variable standards
MUST specify visibility
MUST NOT be prefixed with an underscore if private or protected
e.g. $var1;, private $var2;, protected $var3;
Class methods
MUST follow function standards
MUST specify visibility
MUST NOT be prefixed with an underscore if private or protected
e.g. func1(), private func2(), protected func3()
Class instance
MUST start with capital letter
MUST be camelcase
MUST include parenthesis
e.g. $user = new User();, $OfficeProgram = new OfficeProgram();
‚ñ≤ Table of Contents

1. Class File
Class file MUST only contain one definition and MUST be prefixed with class-.

‚úñ Incorrect
Filename: class-user.php

<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class User
{
	// ...
}

class Office
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because User and Office are defined in one file.

Filename: user.php

<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class User
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because filename is not prefixed with class-.

‚úî Correct
Filename: class-user.php

<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class User
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
Filename: class-office.php

<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class Office
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Classes

2. Class Namespace
Class namespace MUST be defined and MUST include vendor name.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

class User
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because there is no namespace defined.

<?php

namespace Model;

class User
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because vendor name is missing in the namespace name.

‚úî Correct
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class User
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Classes

3. Class Name
Class name MUST start with a capital letter and MUST be camelcase.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class officeProgram
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because officeProgram does not start with a capital letter.

<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class Officeprogram
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because Officeprogram is not camelcase.

‚úî Correct
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class OfficeProgram
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Classes

4. Class Documentation
Class documentation MUST be present and MUST use phpDocumentor tag style.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class User
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because User is missing documentation.

<?php

namespace MyCompany\View;

/**
 * User View
 */
class User
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because User is missing phpDocumentor tags.

‚úî Correct
<?php

namespace MyCompany\View;

/**
 * User View
 *
 * @author Firstname Lastname
 * @global object $post
 * @package MyCompany\API
 */
class User
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Classes

5. Class Definition
Class definition MUST place curly braces on their own line.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class User {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because { is not on its own line.

‚úî Correct
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class User
{
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Classes

6. Class Properties
Class properties:

MUST follow variable standards
MUST specify visibility
MUST NOT be prefixed with an underscore if private or protected
‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class User
{
	// Public
	$var1;

	// Protected
	$var2;

	// Private
	$var3;
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because visibility is not specified for $var1, $var2 and $var3.

<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class User
{
	public $var1;
	protected $_var2;
	private $_var3;
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because protected and private properties are prefixed with _.

‚úî Correct
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class User
{
	public $var1;
	protected $var2;
	private $var3;
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Classes

7. Class Methods
Class methods:

MUST follow function standards
MUST specify visibility
MUST NOT be prefixed with an underscore if private or protected
‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class User
{
	// ...

	// Public
	function get_var1() {
		return $this->var1;
	}

	// Protected
	function get_var2() {
		return $this->var2;
	}

	// Private
	function get_var3() {
		return $this->var3;
	}
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because visibility is not specified for get_var1(), get_var2() and get_var3().

<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class User
{
	// ...

	public function get_var1() {
		return $this->var1;
	}

	protected function _get_var2() {
		return $this->var2;
	}

	private function _get_var3() {
		return $this->var3;
	}
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because protected and private methods are prefixed with _.

‚úî Correct
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class User
{
	// ...

	public function get_var1() {
		return $this->var1;
	}

	protected function get_var2() {
		return $this->var2;
	}

	private function get_var3() {
		return $this->var3;
	}
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Classes

8. Class Instance
Class instance:

MUST follow variable standards
MUST include parenthesis
‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

$office_program = new OfficeProgram;

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because new OfficeProgram is missing parenthesis.

‚úî Correct
<?php

$office_program = new OfficeProgram();

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Classes

12. Best Practices
Variable initialization SHOULD occur prior to use and SHOULD occur early
e.g. $var1 = '';, $var2 = 0;
Initialization/declaration order
MUST lead with globals, follow with constants, conclude with local variables
MUST lead with properties and follow with methods in classes
MUST lead with public, follow with protected, conclude with private methods in classes
SHOULD be alphabetical within their type
i.e. global $var1;, define('VAR2', '');, $var3 = 0;
Globals SHOULD NOT be used
i.e. no global $var;
Explicit expressions SHOULD be used
e.g. if ($expr === false), while ($expr !== true)
E_STRICT reporting MUST NOT trigger errors
i.e. do not use deprecated functions, etc.
‚ñ≤ Table of Contents

1. Variable Initialization
Variable initialization SHOULD occur prior to use and SHOULD occur early.

~ Acceptable
<?php

$movies = get_movies();

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Acceptable, but $movies should be initialized prior to use.

<?php

if ($expr) {
	// ....
}

$movies = array();
$movies = get_movies();

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Acceptable, but $movies should be initialized earlier.

‚úî Preferred
<?php

$movies = array();

if ($expr) {
	// ....
}

$movies = get_movies();

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Best Practices

2. Initialization/Declaration Order
Initialization/declaration order:

MUST lead with globals, follow with constants, conclude with local variables
MUST lead with properties and follow with methods in classes
MUST lead with public, follow with protected, conclude with private methods in classes
SHOULD be alphabetical within their type
‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

define('ENVIRONMENT', 'PRODUCTION');

$id = 0;

global $app_config;

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because $app_config is not first, ENVIRONMENT not second, and $id not third.

<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class Office
{
	public function get_name() {
		// ...
	}

	private $name;
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because get_name() is declared before $name.

<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class Office
{
	private $id;
	private $name;
	private $status;

	private function get_name() {
		// ...
	}

	public function get_id() {
		// ...
	}

	protected function get_status() {
		// ...
	}
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because get_id() is not first, get_status() not second, and get_name() not third.

~ Acceptable
<?php

global $db_connection,
	$app_config,
	$cache;

define('MODE', 1);
define('ENVIRONMENT', 'PRODUCTION');

$id = 0;
$firstname = '';
$lastname = '';

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Acceptable, but the globals and constants should be in alphabetical order.

<?php

function get_movies() {
	// ...
}

function get_actors() {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Acceptable, but get_actors should be declared before get_movies.

‚úî Correct
<?php

global $app_config,
	$cache,
	$db_connection;

define('ENVIRONMENT', 'PRODUCTION');
define('MODE', 1);

$id = 0;
$firstname = '';
$lastname = '';

// EOF
 
<?php

namespace MyCompany\Model;

class Office
{
	private $id;
	private $name;
	private $status;

	public function get_id() {
		// ...
	}

	protected function get_status() {
		// ...
	}

	private function get_name() {
		// ...
	}
}

// EOF
 
‚úî Preferred
<?php

function get_actors() {
	// ...
}

function get_movies() {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Best Practices

3. Globals
Globals SHOULD NOT be used.

~ Acceptable
<?php

$pdo = new PDO('mysql:host=localhost;dbname=test', $user, $pass);

function get_user($id) {
	global $pdo;
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Acceptable, but global variables should be avoided.

‚úî Preferred
<?php

function get_database_object() {
	return new PDO('mysql:host=localhost;dbname=test', $user, $pass);
}

function get_user($id) {
	$pdo = get_database_object();
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Best Practices

4. Explicit Expressions
Explicit expressions SHOULD be used.

~ Acceptable
<?php

if ($expr == true) {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Acceptable, but === could be used here instead.

‚úî Preferred
<?php

if ($expr === true) {
	// ...
}

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Best Practices

5. E_STRICT Reporting
E_STRICT reporting MUST NOT trigger errors.

‚úñ Incorrect
<?php

$firstname = call_user_method('get_firstname', $User);

// EOF
 
‚Ü≥ Incorrect because call_user_method (deprecated) will cause E_STRICT warning.

‚úî Correct
<?php

$firstname = call_user_func(array($User, 'get_firstname'));

// EOF
 
‚ñ≤ Best Practices

‚ñ≤ Table of Contents

